I would argue that if you're complaining about using ChatGPT for its relative wokeness/lack of wokeness, you're probably using it wrong. I get it that there are some folks who are interested in slicing wokeness into a million pieces to explain it.

Yes, ChatGPT has a liberal bias. It's because its main opponents are probably in New York, where a lot of publishing gets done, and to get gatekeepers on board, you have to appear woke to satisfy their ivory tower leanings these days. I can live with that.

Perhaps it's no longer relevant. In a way, ChatGPT mocks humans' hubris for understanding literature. It's bad sometimes, but not more often than humans are bad. This parameter can be tuned by using more descriptive dialogue as you work things out.

This is not to say that one should give in. It means that the educational tools we have right now are immense. I think ChatGPT will be as legendary as Excel in the long run. It's Excel for writers. But is it Turing complete? Who knows? I don't even know what that means anymore.

Anyway, this is to say that much of our contemporary issues with things like ChatGPT and Midjourney and Lensa, is because we insist on calling them "intelligences," whereas other similar generative platforms are only -BRANDED- as AI, but -UNDERSTOOD- as algorithmic platforms.

To wit: ChatGPT isn't "writing" so much as it is engaging in sophisticated pattern analysis based on its corpus of text and generating text that appears "human-like" on the basis of algorithmic prediction. Prediction which, mind you, can be hilariously wrong in a variety of ways.

Calling something an "AI" leads to the assumption that the algorithmic platform is operating independently of human input, that it is somehow  "thinking" on its own without being programmed to do so. ChatGPT and other generators are doing no such thing.

Moreover, it leads to assumptions about what it can and cannot do and increased unwarranted confidence in algorithmic platforms. The whole "can ChatGPT write an essay for me" crisis (lmao) in education is a product of this conflation between "AI" and "algorithm."

This isn't me trying to pull what Nick Bostrom (lol) calls the "AI effect," or treating whatever it is that AI hasn't done as "artificial intelligence;" this is me pointing to the fact that calling something like ChatGPT or Midjourney or Stable Diffusion "AI" has social effects.

For example, referring to ChatGPT as "an algorithmic platform trained on a large corpus of text to predict the next sentence in a passage which allows it to generate human-like responses to queries," rather than an "AI platform," avoids the obfuscation and implications of AI.

ChatGPT isn't ready to crack the coding interview yet.

But it's still good at coming up with a high level plan, and writing a buggy implementation.

These stats consider a "correct answer" to be passing all the test cases.

But if we lower the bar to passing just one test case, things look a lot better.

ChatGPT is good at generating somewhat working, but buggy code. https://t.co/lOEvgqHFJ0

ChatGPT does fairly well at solving easy questions (77%).

But does badly at medium questions (16%).

And fails entirely at hard questions (0%).

Telling it how to solve the problem at a high level doesn't help very much. https://t.co/D6ldrSCEE4

ChatGPT sucks at coding interviews.

It can only solve 28% of LeetCode questions.

And it's only good at solving easy questions that aren't asked in interviews.

While a future version of ChatGPT may lead to the end of LeetCode interviews, we really aren't there yet. https://t.co/qfuezJhmBV
